Great, so it looks like we have a phyloseq object that contains: 735 taxa in 47 samples 47 samples with 3 sample variables 735 taxa by 7 taxonomic ranks And, at least 608 have taxonomy assigned to Phylum level

Pruning

Not all of the taxa will be informative, and some may be outliers and cause problems in the analysis. So, well filter / prune them out of the full data set for some analyses.

tarspot_physeq
#Filter out OTUS that don't appear > 5 times in at least 5% of the samples
tarspot_filtered <- genefilter_sample(tarspot_physeq, filterfun_sample(function(x) x > 5),
                                      A=.05*nsamples(tarspot_physeq))
tarspot_pruned <- prune_taxa(tarspot_filtered, tarspot_physeq)
tarspot_pruned <- transform_sample_counts(tarspot_pruned, function(x) 1E6 * x/sum(x))
tarspot_pruned

So, removing OTUs low abundance (< 5) and are in fewer than 5% of samples reduces the number of taxa in our data set from 735 to 218. While this seems like a large reduction, I think its a reasonably relaxed filtering strategy. Lets start exploring the data.

Alpha Diversity

Lets check the alpha diversity of species within each lesion type using Shannons index

theme_set(theme_bw())
p <- plot_richness(tarspot_physeq, x="plant_status", measures="Shannon") +
  geom_boxplot()
p

Using the full dataset (tarspot_physeq) and the pruned dataset (tarspot_pruned) yield very similar plots. They show that the Control and tar spot samples seem to have higher diversity measurements. Perhaps the lack of diversity among Fish eye samples is due to a higher abundance of necrotic tissues that make it harder for most species to survive and thrive here.

Since the no ethanol controls match their respective lesion types, merge them in with their lesion typs and re-run the diversity plot

alpha <- tarspot_pruned
alpha@sam_data$plant_status <- as.character(alpha@sam_data$plant_status)
alpha@sam_data$plant_status[alpha@sam_data$plant_status=="Tar spot no ethanol"] <- "Tar spot"

Again, the full dataset and the pruned dataset yield very similar plots. The Shannon index still shows interesting differences between Fish eye symptoms and the others, so lets take a look at richness and evenness, which are both parts of the Shannon index calculation. This idea / code is largely taken from: https://github.com/joey711/phyloseq/issues/945

alpha_diversity <- estimate_richness(tarspot_physeq, measure = c("Shannon", "Observed"))
H <- alpha_diversity$Shannon
S1 <- alpha_diversity$Observed
S <- log(S1)
evenness <- H/S
alpha_diversity$Evenness = evenness
#Again, merge the "no ethanol" controls with their respective symptoms
tarspot_meta$plant_status <- as.character(tarspot_meta$plant_status)

So, overall it seems like the Fish eye lesions are associated with lower observed taxa (lower richness) and lower evenness. This indicates that Fish eye lesions are likely dominated by a single taxa, or small group of unique taxa, compared to Tar spot lesions and Healthy tissues. If thats the case, we can likely identify candidate taxa that are dominating in the Fish eye lesions.

Now lets look at taxa associated with each sample. At this point, there are far too many OTUs in the full dataset (tarspot_physeq), so use the pruned dataset (tarspot_pruned), which is also normalized to the sample with the lowest read depth.

Its a bit harder to make sense of this plot, but it sort of confirms what the alpha diversity analysis shows - Fish eye lesions have fewer, larger blocks of species while Tar spot lesions have more, smaller blocks of species, indicating more diversity. Of note, the Fusarium and Nigrospora(?) blocks are larger in the Fish eye lesions.

Lets see if the communities for each type of lesion are different by running a PERMANOVA on the distance matrix, as a function of lesion type.

tarspot_physeq@sam_data$plant_status <- as.character(tarspot_physeq@sam_data$plant_status)
tarspot_physeq@sam_data$plant_status[tarspot_physeq@sam_data$plant_status=="Tar spot no ethanol"] <- "Tar spot"
tarspot_physeq@sam_data$plant_status[tarspot_physeq@sam_data$plant_status=="Fish eye no ethanol"] <- "Fish eye"
tarspot_physeq@sam_data$plant_status[tarspot_physeq@sam_data$plant_status=="Control"] <- "Healthy"
tarspot_physeq@sam_data$plant_status <- as.factor(tarspot_physeq@sam_data$plant_status)
tarspot_physeq@sam_data$plant_status <- relevel(tarspot_physeq@sam_data$plant_status, "Healthy")
#Calculate distance matrix
tarspot_dist <- phyloseq::distance(tarspot_physeq, method = "bray")
#Create a list of lesion types
lesion_type <- tarspot_physeq@sam_data$plant_status
#Run PERMNAOVA
adonis(tarspot_dist ~ lesion_type)
## 
## Call:
## adonis(formula = tarspot_dist ~ lesion_type) 
## 
## Permutation: free
## Number of permutations: 999
## 
## Terms added sequentially (first to last)
## 
##             Df SumsOfSqs MeanSqs F.Model      R2 Pr(>F)    
## lesion_type  2    3.0493 1.52467  10.197 0.31672  0.001 ***
## Residuals   44    6.5786 0.14951         0.68328           
## Total       46    9.6279                 1.00000           
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
#Post hoc test for PERMANOVA
p.hoc <- betadisper(tarspot_dist, lesion_type)
TukeyHSD(p.hoc)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = distances ~ group, data = df)
## 
## $group
##                           diff         lwr         upr     p adj
## Fish eye-Healthy   0.131046599 -0.04314455  0.30523775 0.1734066
## Tar spot-Healthy   0.001208233 -0.17298292  0.17539938 0.9998440
## Tar spot-Fish eye -0.129838366 -0.21517425 -0.04450248 0.0017444

Great! Lesion types have significantly different communities according to PERMANOVA (adonis). The betadisper function can be used to assess beta diversity, and the Tukey test indicates that the Fish eye community is significantly different from the Tar spot community.

Ordination plots

Since this is a large dataset, it helps to look at the data with ordination methods, calculated by different distance metrics. So, lets generate a PCoA plot to visualize these communities. Lets use bray-curtis distances, as these are commonly used in ecological data. Since well want to explore taxa associated with each lesion type, well have to use the pruned dataset, or else the plots get too messy.

tarspot_ord <- ordinate(pooled_pruned, "PCoA", "bray")
#PCoA plot
p2 <- plot_ordination(pooled_pruned, tarspot_ord, 
                     type="sample", color="plant_status", shape="plant_status") + 
  geom_point(size=5) + 
  stat_ellipse(level = 0.95) + 
  scale_shape_discrete(name="Lesion Type") + 
  scale_color_discrete(name="Lesion Type") + 
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(face="bold", size = 20),
        axis.title.y = element_text(face="bold", size = 20),
        axis.text = element_text(face="bold", size = 15),
        legend.title = element_text(face="bold", size = 20),
        legend.text = element_text(face="bold", size = 20),
        legend.key.size = unit(2, 'lines'))
  
p2
## Too few points to calculate an ellipse

Great, it looks like Fish eye and Tar spot separate into unique groups based on their fungal communities, which is what we expect after the PERMANOVA results above. Interestingly, the Healthy control samples are somewhere between the two lesion types, but according to the TukeyHSD test above, it is not significantly different from either lesion type. Lets see if we can identify specific taxa associated with each lesion type, again using the pruned dataset.

Along with BLAST data, three species indicative of Fish eye are actually Phyllachora maydis (OTU_262, OTU_33 from BLAST, OTU_1). Another one (OTU_207) is also likely P. maydis, as it is classified to the Order Phyllachorales. The others are a Fungus (OTU_2), an Ascomycete (OTU_8), a Fusarium sp. (OTU_7), and a Paraphaeosphaeria species (OTU_6).

Im begining to wonder if there are isolates of P. maydis that are capable of causing fish eye lesions, and other isolates that cannot. Almost like a race thing. And the Phyllachora indicator species of Fish eye lesions are actually indicating a race / pathovar that is capable of causing the fish eye lesions on its own?
